<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,433,629]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,309,537,561]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
The dissected genitalia of the only known male of this species was found to be missing its aedeagus. However, in all other respects this species comes close to other 
<taxonomicName box="[828,1037,572,595]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Bampurius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[828,945,572,595]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Bampurius</emphasis>
species.
</taxonomicName>
External distiguishing features of the genus are the head markings (
<figureCitation box="[469,560,606,629]" captionStart="FIGURES 52–53" captionStartId="62.[151,269,1614,1638]" captionTargetBox="[250,1406,197,1586]" captionTargetId="figure-58@62.[151,1436,175,1671]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="FIGURES 52–53. Deltocephalinae genera. 52, Paramesodes iraniensis sp. nov., o: subgenital plate, style, aedeagus and connective, dorsal view; j: male pygofer, dorsal view; q: male pygofer, lateral view. 53, Bampurius melichari (Distant), o: valve, subgenital plate and style, dorsal view." pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 53a</figureCitation>
), long antennae and recurved costal forewing veins.
</paragraph>
